<section xml:id="review-solving-quadratic-equations">
  <title>Solving Quadratic Equations Chapter Review</title>

  <subsection>
    <title>Solving Quadratic Equations by Using a Square Root</title>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="section-solving-quadratic-equations-by-using-a-square-root">Section</xref>
      we covered how to solve quadratic equations using the <xref ref="fact-square-root-property" text="title">square root property</xref>
      and how to use the <xref ref="theorem-pythagorean-theorem" text="title">Pythagorean Theorem</xref>.
    </p>

    <example>
      <title>Solving Quadratic Equations Using the Square Root Property</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve for <m>w</m> in <m>3(2-w)^2-24=0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          It's important here to suppress any urge you may have to expand the squared binomial.
          We begin by isolating the squared expression.
          <md>
            <mrow>3(2-w)^2-24\amp=0</mrow>
            <mrow>3(2-w)^2\amp=24</mrow>
            <mrow>(2-w)^2\amp=8</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Now that we have the squared expression isolated,
          we can use the square root property.
          <md>
            <mrow>2-w\amp=-\sqrt{8}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp2-w\amp=\sqrt{8}</mrow>
            <mrow>2-w\amp=-\sqrt{\highlight{4}\cdot2}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp2-w\amp=\sqrt{\highlight{4}\cdot2}</mrow>
            <mrow>2-w\amp=-\sqrt{\highlight{4}}\cdot\sqrt{2}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp2-w\amp=\sqrt{\highlight{4}}\cdot\sqrt{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>2-w\amp=-\highlight{2}\sqrt{2}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp2-w\amp=\highlight{2}\sqrt{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>-w\amp=-2\sqrt{2}-2\amp\text{or}\amp\amp-w\amp=2\sqrt{2}-2</mrow>
            <mrow>w\amp=2\sqrt{2}+2\amp\text{or}\amp\amp w\amp=-2\sqrt{2}+2</mrow>
          </md>
          The solution set is <m>\left\{2\sqrt{2}+2,-2\sqrt{2}+2\right\}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <title>The Pythagorean Theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Faven was doing some wood working in her garage.
          She needed to cut a triangular piece of wood for her project that had a hypotenuse of <m>16</m> inches,
          and the sides of the triangle should be equal in length.
          How long should she make her sides?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let's start by representing the length of the triangle,
          measured in inches, by the letter <m>x</m>.
          That would also make the other side <m>x</m> inches long.
        </p>

        <figure>
          <caption>Piece of wood with labels for Faven</caption>
          <image width="47%">
            <description></description>
            <latex-image>
              <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[axis x line=none,
                            axis y line=none,
                            xmin=0,
                            xmax=1,
                            ymin=0,
                            ymax=1]
                  \addplot[thin,fill=wood] coordinates{(0.1,0.1)(0.9,0.1)(0.9,0.9)(0.1,0.9)(0.1,0.1)};
                  \addplot[dashed, very thick, color=firstcolor] coordinates{(0.1,0.1)(0.9,0.1)(0.9,0.9)(0.1,0.1)};
                  \draw [below] (axis cs:0.5,0.1) node {$x$};
                  \draw [dashed] (axis cs:0.1,0.1) -- (axis cs:0.9,0.9) node[sloped,above] {$16\,\text{in}$};
                  \draw [right] (axis cs:0.9,0.5) node {$x$};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          Faven should now set up the Pythagorean theorem regarding the picture.
          That would be
          <me>
            x^2+x^2=16^2
          </me>
          Solving this equation, we have:
          <md>
            <mrow>x^2+x^2\amp=16^2</mrow>
            <mrow>2x^2\amp=256</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2\amp=128</mrow>
            <mrow>\highlight{\sqrt{\unhighlight{x^2}}}\amp=\highlight{\sqrt{\unhighlight{128}}}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=\sqrt{\highlight{64}\cdot2}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=\sqrt{\highlight{64}}\cdot\sqrt{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=\highlight{8}\sqrt{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp\approx11.3</mrow>
          </md>
          Faven should make the sides of her triangle about <m>11.3</m> inches long to force the hypotenuse to be <m>16</m> inches long.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>The Quadratic Formula</title>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="section-the-quadratic-formula">Section</xref>
      we covered how to use the <xref ref="fact-the-quadratic-formula" text="title">quadratic formula</xref>
      to solve any quadratic equation,
      as well as an <xref ref="algorithm-solving-linear-and-quadratic-equations" text="title">algorithm</xref>
      to help solve linear and quadratic equations.
    </p>

    <example>
      <title>Solving Quadratic Equations with the Quadratic Formula</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the equations using the quadratic formula.

          <ol label="a." cols="2">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>x^2+4x=6</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>5x^2-2x+1=0</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol label="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                First we should change the equation into standard form.
                <md>
                  <mrow>x^2+4x\amp=6</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2+4x-6\amp=0</mrow>
                </md>
                Next, we check and see that we cannot factor the left side or use the square root property so we must use the quadratic formula.
                We identify that <m>\substitute{a=1}</m>,
                <m>\substitute{b=4}</m>, and <m>\substitute{c=-6}</m>.
                We will substitute them into the quadratic formula:
                <md>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{-\substitute{4}\pm\sqrt{(\substitute{4})^2-4(\substitute{1})(\substitute{-6})}}{2(\substitute{1})}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{-4\pm\sqrt{16+24}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{-4\pm\sqrt{40}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{-4\pm\sqrt{\highlight{4}\cdot10}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{-4\pm\sqrt{\highlight{4}}\cdot\sqrt{10}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{-4\pm\highlight{2}\sqrt{10}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=-\frac{4}{2}\pm\frac{2\sqrt{10}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=-2\pm\sqrt{10}</mrow>
                </md>
                So the solution set is <m>\left\{-2+\sqrt{10},-2-\sqrt{10}\right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Since the equation <m>5x^2-2x+1=0</m> is already in standard form,
                we check and see that we cannot factor the left side or use the square root property so we must use the quadratic formula.
                We identify that <m>\substitute{a=5}</m>,
                <m>\substitute{b=-2}</m>, and <m>\substitute{c=1}</m>.
                We will substitute them into the quadratic formula:
                <md>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{-\substitute{(-2)}\pm\sqrt{\substitute{(-2)}^2-4(\substitute{5})(\substitute{1})}}{2(\substitute{5})}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{2\pm\sqrt{4-20}}{10}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{2\pm\sqrt{-16}}{10}</mrow>
                </md>
                Since the solutions have square roots of negative numbers,
                we must conclude that there are no real solutions.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Solving Equations in General</title>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="section-solving-equations-in-general">Section</xref>
      we reviewed how to <xref ref="section-solving-mulitstep-linear-equations" text="title">solve linear equations</xref>, <xref ref="section-solving-quadratic-equations-by-using-a-square-root" text="title">solve quadratic equations using a square root</xref>, <xref ref="section-the-quadratic-formula" text="title">solve quadratic equations with the quadratic formula</xref>, and <xref ref="section-solving-radical-equations" text="title">solve radical equations</xref>.
    </p>

    <example>
      <title>Determining the Type of Equation</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine whether the equations are linear, quadratic, radical, or something else.
          <ol label="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\sqrt[3]{3x-1}-2=-3</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>3x^3-5x^2=2x+1</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(5x-4)^2=2-x</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>3+\sqrt{3x-1}=x</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\sqrt{5}(2x-3)=19-3x</m>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>2x^2-3x+7=19</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Determine whether the equations are linear, quadratic, radical, or something else.
          <ol label="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>\sqrt[3]{3x-1}-2=-3</m> is a radical equation. Since a cube root appears in the equation with the variable inside, it is automatically a radical equation.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>3x^3-5x^2=2x+1</m> is not a linear, quadratic, or radical equation, so it must be <q>something else</q>. It is a cubic equation, which is beyond the scope of this book.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>(5x-4)^2=2-x</m> is a quadratic equation. Since the variable will have a square, but no higher power, it is quadratic.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>3+\sqrt{3x-1}=x</m> is a radical equation. The square root with the variable inside makes this equation radical.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>\sqrt{5}(2x-3)=19-3x</m> is a linear equation. Since the variable is only to the first power and not under any radical itself, this is a linear equation.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>x^2-3x+7=19</m> is a quadratic equation. The variable being squared makes this quadratic.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <title>Equations where the Variable Appears Once</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the equations using an effective method.

          <ol label="a." cols="3">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(x-4)^2-2=0</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\sqrt{3x+2}-2=5</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>3(5x-6)-7=2</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>3(v-2)^2+54=0</m>
              </p>
            </li>

          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol label="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                To solve the equation <m>(x-4)^2-2=0</m>,
                first note that there is no linear term:
                there is only a square and a constant.
                This leads us to consider the square root method.
                Before doing that, isolate the square:
                <md>
                  <mrow>(x-4)^2-2\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>(x-4)^2\amp=2</mrow>
                </md>
                Now we can apply the square root method to the equation.
                <md>
                  <mrow>x-4\amp=\sqrt{2}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x-4\amp=-\sqrt{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=4+\sqrt{2}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp x\amp=4-\sqrt{2}</mrow>
                </md>
                So the solution set is <m>\left\{4+\sqrt{2},4-\sqrt{2}\right\}</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Since the equation <m>\sqrt{3x+2}-2=5</m> is a square root equation, we will need to square both sides eventually. First, we should isolate the radical on one side.
                <md>
                  <mrow>\sqrt{3x+2}-2\amp=5</mrow>
                  <mrow>\sqrt{3x+2}\amp=7</mrow>
                  <mrow>\firsthighlight{\left(\unhighlight{\sqrt{3x+2}}\right)^2}\amp=\firsthighlight{\unhighlight{7}^2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>3x+2\amp=49</mrow>
                  <mrow>3x\amp=47</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{47}{3}</mrow>
                </md>
                Recall that we should verify all solutions to radical equations. So, substituting <m>x=\frac{47}{3}</m>, we have
                <md>
                  <mrow>\sqrt{3\cdot\substitute{\frac{47}{3}}+2}-2\amp\stackrel{?}{=}5</mrow>
                  <mrow>\sqrt{47+2}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}7</mrow>
                  <mrow>\sqrt{49}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}7</mrow>
                  <mrow>7\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}7</mrow>
                </md>
                So, the solution set is <m>\left\{\frac{47}{3}\right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>3(5x-6)-7=2</m> is a linear equation. We should simplify and then try to isolate the variable step by step.
                <md>
                  <mrow>3(5x-6)-7\amp=2</mrow>
                  <mrow>15x-18-7\amp=2</mrow>
                  <mrow>15x-25\amp=2</mrow>
                  <mrow>15x\amp=27</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{27}{15}</mrow>
                </md>
                The solution set to the equation <m>3(5x-6)-7=2</m> is <m>\left\{\frac{27}{15}\right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Again, since there is no linear term,
                we should consider the square root method.
                Before doing that, isolate the square:
                <md>
                  <mrow>3(v-2)^2+54\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>3(v-2)^2\amp=-54</mrow>
                  <mrow>(v-2)^2\amp=-18</mrow>
                </md>
                Now we can apply the square root method to the equation.
                <md>
                  <mrow>v-2\amp=-\sqrt{-18}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp v-2\amp=\sqrt{-18}</mrow>
                  <mrow>v-2\amp=-\sqrt{\firsthighlight{9}\cdot\secondhighlight{-1}\cdot2}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp v-2\amp=\sqrt{\firsthighlight{9}\cdot\secondhighlight{-1}\cdot2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>v-2\amp=-\sqrt{\firsthighlight{9}}\cdot\sqrt{\secondhighlight{-1}}\cdot\sqrt{2}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp v-2\amp=\sqrt{\firsthighlight{9}}\cdot\sqrt{\secondhighlight{-1}}\cdot\sqrt{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>v-2\amp=-\firsthighlight{3}\secondhighlight{i}\sqrt{2}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp v-2\amp=\firsthighlight{3}\secondhighlight{i}\sqrt{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>v\amp=2-\firsthighlight{3}\secondhighlight{i}\sqrt{2}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp v\amp=2+\firsthighlight{3}\secondhighlight{i}\sqrt{2}</mrow>
                </md>
                So, the solution set is <m>\left\{2+\firsthighlight{3}\secondhighlight{i}\sqrt{2},2-\firsthighlight{3}\secondhighlight{i}\sqrt{2}\right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <title>Equations With More Than One Instance of the Variable</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use <xref ref="algorithm-solving-linear-and-quadratic-equations"/> to help solve the equations after deciding if they are linear or quadratic.

          <ol label="a." cols="2">

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>(x-4)^2+2x=0</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>2(x-6)^2-16=0</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>16x-2(3x-1)=7</m>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                <m>\sqrt{x+2}=x-4</m>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol label="a.">

            <li>
              <p>
                To solve the equation <m>(x-4)^2+2x=0</m>,
                first note that there is a linear term (<m>+2x</m>), the quadratic formula.
                To use either, we must first put the equation in standard form.
                <md>
                  <mrow>(x-4)^2+2x\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>(x-4)(x-4)+2x\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2-8x+16+2x\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>x^2-6x+16\amp=0</mrow>
                </md>
                Now we must use the quadratic formula.
                First, identify that <m>\substitute{a=1}</m>,
                <m>\substitute{b=-6}</m>, and <m>\substitute{c=16}</m>.
                <md>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{-(\substitute{-6})\pm\sqrt{(\substitute{-6})^2-4(\substitute{1})(\substitute{16})}}{2(\substitute{1})}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{6\pm\sqrt{36-48}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{6\pm\sqrt{-12}}{2}</mrow>
                  <intertext>At this point, we notice that the solutions are complex. Continue to simplify until they are completely reduced.</intertext>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{6\pm\sqrt{\firsthighlight{4}\cdot\secondhighlight{-1}\cdot3}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{6\pm\sqrt{\firsthighlight{4}}\cdot\sqrt{\secondhighlight{-1}}\cdot\sqrt{3}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{6\pm\firsthighlight{2}\secondhighlight{i}\sqrt{3}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{6}{2}\pm\frac{2i\sqrt{3}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=3\pm i\sqrt{3}</mrow>
                </md>
                So the solution set is <m>\left\{3+i\sqrt{3},3-i\sqrt{3}\right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                To solve the equation <m>2(x-6)^2-16=0</m> we first note that it is quadratic.
                Since there is no linear term,
                we should try using the square root method.
                <md>
                  <mrow>2(x-6)^2-16\amp=0</mrow>
                  <mrow>2(x-6)^2\amp=16</mrow>
                  <mrow>(x-6)^2\amp=8</mrow>
                </md>
                <md>
                  <mrow>x-6\amp=\sqrt{8} \amp \text{ or } \amp\amp x-6\amp=-\sqrt{8}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x-6\amp=\sqrt{\highlight{4}\cdot2} \amp \text{ or } \amp\amp x-6\amp=-\sqrt{\highlight{4}\cdot2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x-6\amp=\sqrt{\highlight{4}}\cdot\sqrt{2} \amp \text{ or } \amp\amp x-6\amp=-\sqrt{\highlight{4}}\cdot\sqrt{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x-6\amp=\highlight{2}\sqrt{2} \amp \text{ or } \amp\amp x-6\amp=-\highlight{2}\sqrt{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=6+\highlight{2}\sqrt{2} \amp \text{ or } \amp\amp x\amp=6-\highlight{2}\sqrt{2}</mrow>
                </md>
                So, the solution set is <m>\left\{6+2\sqrt{2},6-2\sqrt{2}\right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                To solve the equation <m>16x-2(3x-1)=3</m> we first we first note that it is linear.
                Since it is linear,
                we just need to isolate the terms with the variable on one side and all the other terms on the other side of the equals sign.
                <md>
                  <mrow>16x-2(3x-1)\amp=7</mrow>
                  <mrow>16x-6x+3\amp=7</mrow>
                  <mrow>10x+3\amp=7</mrow>
                  <mrow>10x\amp=4</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{4}{10}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{2}{5}</mrow>
                </md>
                So, the solution set is <m>\left\{\frac{2}{5}\right\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Since the equation <m>\sqrt{x+2}=x-4</m> is a radical equation, we should isolate the radical (which it already is) and square both sides of the equation.
                <md>
                  <mrow>\sqrt{x+2}\amp=x-4</mrow>
                  <mrow>\firsthighlight{(\unhighlight{\sqrt{x+2}})^2}\amp=\firsthighlight{(\unhighlight{x-4})^2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x+2\amp=(x-4)^2</mrow>
                  <mrow>x+2\amp=x^2-8x+16</mrow>
                  <mrow>0\amp=x^2-9x+14</mrow>
                </md>
                Since the equation is now quadratic, we should use the quadratic formula to solve it.
                First, identify that <m>\substitute{a=1}</m>,
                <m>\substitute{b=-9}</m>, and <m>\substitute{c=14}</m>.
                <md>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{-(\substitute{-9})\pm\sqrt{(\substitute{-9})^2-4(\substitute{1})(\substitute{14})}}{2(\substitute{1})}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{9\pm\sqrt{81-56}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{9\pm\sqrt{25}}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{9\pm5}{2}</mrow>
                </md>
                <md>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{9+5}{2}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=\frac{9-5}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=\frac{14}{2}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=\frac{4}{2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>x\amp=7\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=2</mrow>
                </md>
                Since this is a radical equation, we should verify our solutions to look for <q>extraneous solutions</q>.
                <md>
                  <mrow>\sqrt{\substitute{7}+2}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}\substitute{7}-4\amp\amp\text{or}\amp\sqrt{\substitute{2}+2}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}\substitute{2}-4</mrow>
                  <mrow>\sqrt{9}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}3\amp\amp\text{or}\amp\sqrt{4}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}-2</mrow>
                  <mrow>\sqrt{9}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}3\amp\amp\text{or}\amp\sqrt{4}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}-2</mrow>
                  <mrow>3\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}3\amp\amp\text{or}\amp2\amp\stackrel{no}{=}-2</mrow>
                </md>
                So the solution set is <m>\{7\}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <title>Solving For a Variable in Terms of Other Variables</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Often in science classes, you are given a formula that needs to be rearranged to be useful to a situation. Below are several formulas from physics that describe the natural world.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Solve the equation <m>v^2=v_0^2-2ax</m> for <m>x</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Solve the equation <m>c\cdot l=l_0\sqrt{c^2-v^2}</m> for <m>v</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Solve the equation <m>y=\frac{\alpha t^2}{2}+vt</m> for <m>t</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Solve the equation <m>E^2=m^2c^4+p^2c^2</m> for <m>p</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>v^2=v_0^2-2ax</m> is a basic formula that describes objects moving while accelerating. Since <m>x</m> is to the first power without any other complicating factors, this equation is linear. Solving for <m>x</m> we get:
                <md>
                  <mrow>v^2\amp=v_0^2-2ax</mrow>
                  <mrow>v^2-v_0^2\amp=-2ax</mrow>
                  <mrow>\frac{v^2-v_0^2}{-2a}\amp=x</mrow>
                </md>
                The solution is <m>\frac{v^2-v_0^2}{-2a}</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>c\cdot l=l_0\sqrt{c^2-v^2}</m> describes how lengths get warped when you travel near the speed of light. Since <m>v</m> is inside the square root, we should consider this a radical equation. Solving for <m>v</m>, we get:
                <md>
                  <mrow>c\cdot l\amp=l_0\sqrt{c^2-v^2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\frac{c\cdot l}{l_0}\amp=\sqrt{c^2-v^2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\firsthighlight{\left(\unhighlight{\frac{c\cdot l}{l_0}}\right)^2}\amp=\firsthighlight{\left(\unhighlight{\sqrt{c^2-v^2}}\right)^2}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\frac{c^2\cdot l^2}{l_0^2}\amp=c^2-v^2</mrow>
                  <mrow>\frac{c^2\cdot l^2}{l_0^2}-c^2\amp=-v^2</mrow>
                  <mrow>-\frac{c^2\cdot l^2}{l_0^2}+c^2\amp=v^2</mrow>
                  <intertext>Now we can apply the square root method to solve for <m>v</m>.</intertext>
                  <mrow>\pm\sqrt{-\frac{c^2\cdot l^2}{l_0^2}+c^2}\amp=v</mrow>
                </md>
                So, the solutions are <m>\pm\sqrt{-\frac{c^2\cdot l^2}{l_0^2}+c^2}</m>. Without more context, we shouldn't dismiss the negative solution.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>y=\frac{\alpha t^2}{2}+vt</m> is another formula that describes the movement of accelerating objects. Since <m>t</m> is squared, this is a quadratic equation. Since both <m>t^2</m> and <m>t</m> appear in the equation, we should consider using the quadratic formula. First, we should rearrange the equation to standard form.
                <md>
                  <mrow>y\amp=\frac{\alpha t^2}{2}+vt</mrow>
                  <mrow>0\amp=\frac{\alpha }{2}t^2+vt-y</mrow>
                </md>
                Now, note that <m>\substitute{a=\frac{\alpha }{2}}</m>, <m>\substitute{b=v}</m>, and <m>\substitute{c=-y}</m>.
                <md>
                  <mrow>t\amp=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</mrow>
                  <mrow>t\amp=\frac{-(\substitute{v})\pm\sqrt{(\substitute{v})^2-4(\substitute{\frac{\alpha }{2}})(\substitute{-y})}}{2(\substitute{\frac{\alpha }{2}})}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp=\frac{-v\pm\sqrt{v^2+2\alpha y}}{\alpha }</mrow>
                </md>
                So the solutions are <m>\frac{-v\pm\sqrt{v^2+2\alpha y}}{\alpha }</m>. Without more context, we shouldn't dismiss the negative solution.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The equation <m>E^2=m^2c^4+p^2c^2</m> is a physics formula that relates energy, mass, and momentum with the speed of light. You probably have heard of it's better known cousin <m>E=mc^2</m> which is what this formula simplifies to when there is no momentum. To solve for <m>p</m>, we have to recognize that since <m>p</m> is squared, we need to treat this as a quadratic equation. Since there is no linear term <m>p</m>, we can try the square root method.
                <md>
                  <mrow>E^2\amp=m^2c^4+p^2c^2</mrow>
                  <mrow>E^2-m^2c^4\amp=p^2c^2</mrow>
                  <mrow>\frac{E^2-m^2c^4}{c^2}\amp=p^2</mrow>
                  <intertext>Now we can use the square root method to isolate p.</intertext>
                  <mrow>\pm\sqrt{\frac{E^2-m^2c^4}{c^2}}\amp=p</mrow>
                  <mrow>\pm\frac{\sqrt{E^2-m^2c^4}}{\sqrt{c^2}}\amp=p</mrow>
                  <mrow>\pm\frac{\sqrt{E^2-m^2c^4}}{c}\amp=p</mrow>
                </md>
                So the solutions are <m>\pm\frac{\sqrt{E^2-m^2c^4}}{c}</m>. Without more context, we shouldn't dismiss the negative solution.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
